<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[144,1104,613,804]" box="[144,276,613,637]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">
<heading box="[144,276,613,637]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[144,276,613,637]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[144,1104,613,804]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">
Native to Western Europe/Cosmopolitan (
<bibRefCitation author="Horackova J &amp; Jurickova L" box="[627,986,653,677]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" pagination="63 - 65" refId="ref11154" refString="Horackova J, Jurickova L. 2009. A new record of Oxychilus alliarius (Gastropoda: Zonitidae) with the species distribution in the Czech Republic. Malacol Bohemoslov. 8: 63 - 65." type="journal article" year="2009">Horácková and Juricková 2009</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1044,1103,653,677]" name="Chile" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Chile</collectingCountry>
this species has been recorded in Las Rojas, 
<collectingRegion box="[638,836,684,708]" country="Chile" name="Coquimbo" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Coquimbo region</collectingRegion>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[851,944,684,709]" degrees="29" direction="south" minutes="54" orientation="latitude" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" precision="925" value="-29.9">
29°54 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[916,922,685,709]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">ʹ</emphasis>
S
</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[957,1062,684,709]" degrees="71" direction="west" minutes="10" orientation="longitude" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" precision="925" value="-71.166664">
71°10 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1020,1026,685,709]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">ʹ</emphasis>
W
</geoCoordinate>
), in the Arboretum Park, 
<collectingCountry box="[409,449,716,740]" name="Iceland" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Isla</collectingCountry>
Teja, Valdivia (
<geoCoordinate box="[653,754,716,740]" degrees="39" direction="south" minutes="50" orientation="latitude" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" precision="925" value="-39.833332">
39°50 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[717,723,716,740]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">ʹ</emphasis>
S
</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[774,885,716,740]" degrees="73" direction="west" minutes="14" orientation="longitude" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" precision="925" value="-73.23333">
73°14 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[838,844,716,740]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">ʹ</emphasis>
W
</geoCoordinate>
) and in the Juan Fernández Archipelago (
<bibRefCitation author="Cadiz FJ &amp; Cadiz DG &amp; Grau JH" box="[427,622,748,772]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" pagination="119 - 124" refId="ref9177" refString="Cadiz FJ, Cadiz DG, Grau JH. 2013. An invasive predatory snail Oxychilus alliarius (Miller, 1822) (Stylommatophora: Zonitidae) threatens the native malacofauna of continental Chile: a morphological and molecular confirmation. Stud Neotrop Fauna E. 48: 119 - 124." type="journal article" year="2013">Cádiz et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The first record of this species for 
<collectingCountry box="[1044,1103,748,772]" name="Chile" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Chile</collectingCountry>
was by 
<bibRefCitation author="Odhner NJ" box="[231,398,780,804]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" pagination="219 - 254" refId="ref12592" refString="Odhner NJ. 1922. Mollusca from Juan Fernandez and Easter Island. In: Skottsberg C, editor. The natural history of Juan Fernandez and Easter Island. Vol. 3. Uppsala: Almquist and Wiksells Boktryckeri-A. - B; p. 219 - 254." type="book chapter" year="1922">Odhner (1922)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[144,757,875,939]" box="[144,614,875,899]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">
<heading box="[144,614,875,899]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[144,614,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Possible mechanism of introduction/Status</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[144,757,875,939]" box="[144,757,915,939]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">
Human transportation/established (
<bibRefCitation author="Cadiz FJ &amp; Cadiz DG &amp; Grau JH" box="[546,740,915,939]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" pagination="119 - 124" refId="ref9177" refString="Cadiz FJ, Cadiz DG, Grau JH. 2013. An invasive predatory snail Oxychilus alliarius (Miller, 1822) (Stylommatophora: Zonitidae) threatens the native malacofauna of continental Chile: a morphological and molecular confirmation. Stud Neotrop Fauna E. 48: 119 - 124." type="journal article" year="2013">Cádiz et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[144,1104,1010,1137]" box="[144,242,1010,1034]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">
<heading box="[144,242,1010,1034]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[144,242,1010,1034]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[144,1104,1010,1137]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748">
Carnivore, facultative predator of other small snails (
<bibRefCitation author="Meyer WM &amp; Cowie RH" box="[758,1028,1049,1073]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" pagination="135 - 144" refId="ref12166" refString="Meyer WM, Cowie RH. 2010. Feeding preferences of two predatory snails introduced to Hawaii and their conservation implications. Malacologia. 53: 135 - 144." type="journal article" year="2010">Meyer and Cowie 2010</bibRefCitation>
). This species is known as the “garlic snail” because of its ability to emit a strong smell of garlic when irritated (
<bibRefCitation author="Hayes KA &amp; Yeung NW &amp; Kim JR &amp; Cowie RH" box="[391,589,1113,1137]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1748" pagination="21 - 28" refId="ref11004" refString="Hayes KA, Yeung NW, Kim JR, Cowie RH. 2012. New records of alien Gastropoda in the Hawaiian Islands. Occas pap Bernice P Bishop Mus. 112: 21 - 28." type="journal article" year="2012">Hayes et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). EA, I.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
